icating Risk and Safety -- t13 Risk Communication: A Communication Ethics Perspective -- t14 The Ethic of First and Second Things in Communicating Risk and Safety -- t15 Ethical Obligations in Communicating Risk and Safety: Standards of Dialogue, Uncertainty, Change, and Truthfulness -- tSection 4: Cultural Imperatives When Communicating Risk and Safety -- t16 Culture-centered Approach to Risk Communication -- t17 “All Knowledge Is Local”: The PEN-3 Model as a Guide to Overcoming Western/ European Bias in Risk Communication about Global Health Concerns in East Africa -- t18 Communities of Practice Approach to Safety Communication -- tSection 5: Instructional Perspectives and Compliance-Gaining When Communicating Risk and Safety -- t19 Instruction as Self-Protection -- t20 Mobile Instructional Communication for Public Safety and Community Resilience -- t21 From Risks to Crisis Society: The Drivers of the Public Health Communication Paradigm Shift -- t22 Earthquake Risk Communication of Individual Protective Actions for Big Earthquakes: A Situational Choreography Model Based on Social Communication Engineering -- tSection 6: Media and Technological Considerations When Communicating Risk and Safety -- t23 Risk Information Seeking and Processing Model -- t24 Understanding Contemporary Infodemics through the Risk Amplification through Media Spread (RAMS) Model -- t25 Spotting Risks: How to Integrate Social Media Listening to a Framework of Assessing Risks -- t26 Emergent Organizations and Post-Disaster Risk: Volunteerism in the Digital Age -- t27 Communicating and Perceiving Risks of Artificial Intelligence as an Emerging Technology -- tSection 7: Future Considerations: Untangling Issues of (Mis)Trust When Communicating Risk and Safety -- t28 The Role of Trust and Distrust in Risk and Safety Communication -- t29 It’s Complicated . . . : Exploring Vaccination Attitudes and the Vaccination Infodemic in the UK throughout the COVID-19 Pandemic -- t30 Communicating to Mitigate Behavioral Cyber Risks: The Case of Employee Vulnerability -- t31 Building or Unbuilding Trust? A Reflection on Governments, News Media, and Businesses’ Communication during the COVID-19 Pandemic -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe world is wrought with risks that may harm people and cost lives. The news is riddled with reports of natural disasters (wildfires, floods, earthquakes, hurricanes), industrial disasters (chemical spills, water and air pollution), and health pandemics (e.g., SARS, H1NI, COVID19). Effective risk communication is critical to mitigating harms. The body of research in this handbook reveals the challenges of communicating such messages, affirms the need for dialogue, embraces the role of instruction in proactively communicating risk, acknowledges the function of competing risk messages, investigates the growing influence of new media, and constantly reconsiders the ethical imperative for communicating recommendations for enhanced safety.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Communication Studies.2bisacsh  aRisk Communication.  aRisk Management.  aRisk Preparedness.  aRisk.  aSafety Communication.1 aAlberti, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnthony, Kathryn E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArnett, Ronald C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBean, Hamilton, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeckham, Jessica R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBjörck, Albena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBr